<section xml:id="linear-systems-basics">
	<title>Linear System Basics</title>

	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<!-- INTRODUCTION                                                     -->
	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<introduction>
		<p>
			After exploring uncoupled, partially coupled, and fully coupled systems, we now turn to
			the most tractable and widely used class: <em>linear systems with constant coefficients</em>.
		</p>
		<p>
			Their algebraic form is simple enough for exact analysis, yet flexible enough to model
			everything from harmonic oscillators to interacting populations.  Our first task is to
			define what ‚Äúlinear‚Äù means and show how a short piece of matrix notation can replace a
			page-full of equations.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<!-- 1.  DEFINITION & BASIC EXAMPLES                                  -->
	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<subsection xml:id="linear-definition">
		<title>What Makes a System Linear?</title>

		<p>
			A system is <em>linear</em> if every equation is linear with respect to its dependent variables (all to the power of one). For two variables
			<m>x(t)</m> and <m>y(t)</m> general form is
		</p>

		<md>
			<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = a x + b y</mrow>
			<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = c x + d y</mrow>
		</md>

		<p>
			where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>d</m> are constants.  
			The system is therefore <em>autonomous</em> (no explicit <m>t</m>) and
			<em>planar</em> (two-dimensional).
		</p>

		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Select of linearity of each equation, then select the linearity of the system.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<areas>
				<p>
				<tabular>
					<row>
						<cell><me>\frac{dx}{dt}=</me></cell><cell><m>2x + 3y</m></cell><cell/><cell><area correct="yes">linear</area> ‚Äî <area correct="no">nonlinear</area></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><me>\frac{dy}{dt}=</me></cell><cell><m>xy</m></cell><cell/><cell><area correct="no">linear</area> ‚Äî <area correct="yes">nonlinear</area></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
				<tabular>
					<row>
						<cell>The system as a whole is:</cell><cell/><cell><area correct="no">linear</area> ‚Äî <area correct="yes">nonlinear</area></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</p>
			</areas>
		</exercise>

	</subsection>

	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<!-- 2.  MATRIX / VECTOR FORMULATION                                  -->
	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<subsection xml:id="matrix-form">
		<title>The Matrix Formulation</title>

		<p>
			Writing the same system once more,
		</p>

		<md>
			<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = a x + b y</mrow>
			<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = c x + d y</mrow>
		</md>

		<p>
			define the coefficient matrix and state vector
		</p>

		<me>
			A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix},
			\qquad
			Y = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix},
			\qquad
			\frac{dY}{dt} = \begin{bmatrix} \dfrac{dx}{dt} \\ \dfrac{dy}{dt} \end{bmatrix}
		</me>

		<p>
			Matrix multiplication then packages both equations into the single vector equation
		</p>

		<me>
			\frac{dY}{dt} = AY.
		</me>

		<p>
			This compact format presents the system as a single equation, linking directly to linear algebra tools like eigenvalues, which we will explore later.
		</p>
	</subsection>

	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<!-- 3.  HIGHER-DIMENSION GENERALIZATION (BRIEF)                       -->
	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<subsection xml:id="n-dim-linear">
		<title>From Two to <m>n</m> Dimensions</title>

		<p>
			For <m>n</m> variables <m>y_1,\dots,y_n</m> a constant-coefficient linear system reads
		</p>

		<me>
			\frac{dY}{dt} = AY,
			\qquad
			Y = \begin{bmatrix} y_1 \\ \vdots \\ y_n \end{bmatrix},
			\quad
			A = \begin{bmatrix}
				a_{11} \amp a_{12} \amp \dots \amp a_{1n} \\
				\vdots \amp        \amp \ddots \amp \vdots \\
				a_{n1} \amp a_{n2} \amp \dots \amp a_{nn}
			\end{bmatrix}.
		</me>

		<p>
			The dimension of the system equals the length of <m>Y</m>.  
			Our focus this chapter remains on the planar case (<m>n=2</m>) where geometry and
			algebra meet most clearly.
		</p>

		<p>
			The number of dependent variables is called the <em>dimension</em> of the system. For example, the three-dimensional system:
		</p>

		<exercise label="coeff-matrix-chkpt-1">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Give the coefficient matrix, <m>A</m>, for the following system: 
					<md>
						<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = 3x - 2y</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = z</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{dz}{dt} \amp = 3x - y + 2z</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="10% 32% 3%" margins="27% 28%" valign="middle">
						<p><me>A=\left[\begin{array}{c}\\\\\\\\\\\end{array}\right.</me>		</p>
						<p>
							<tabular>
								<row>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="3" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="-2" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="0" /></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="0" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="0" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="1" /></cell>
								</row>
								<row>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="3" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="-1" /></cell>
									<cell><fillin width="1" mode="string" answer="2" /></cell>
								</row>
							</tabular>	
						</p>
						<p><me>\left.\begin{array}{c}\\\\\\\\\\\end{array}\right]</me>		</p>
					</sidebyside>

					

				</p>
			</statement>
			
			<evaluation>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>3</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>\-\s*2</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>0</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>0</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>0</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>1</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>3</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>\-\s*1</strcmp></test></evaluate>
				<evaluate><test correct="yes"><strcmp>2</strcmp></test></evaluate>
			</evaluation>
		</exercise>
	</subsection>

	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<!-- WRAP-UP + READING QUESTIONS                                      -->
	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<assemblage label="linear-systems-wrap-up">
		<title>üì§ Wrap-Up</title>
		<p>
			<paragraphs label="linear-systems-takeaways">
				<title>üóùÔ∏è Key Takeaways..</title>
				<ul marker="square">
					<li>A system is <em>linear</em> if its unknowns appear without products, powers, or nonlinear functions.</li>
					<li>We'll focus on constant-coefficient linear systems, where the coefficients don't change over time.</li>
					<li>These systems can be written in vector form: <m>\dfrac{dY}{dt} = AY</m>.</li>
				</ul>
			</paragraphs>

			<paragraphs label="linear-systems-cyu">
				<title>Check Your Understanding</title>

				<exercise label="linear-systems-cyu-bundle">
					<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e>  Linear System Basics</title>

						<task label="rq-linear-1">
							<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e>  Linear or Not?</title>
							<statement>
								<p>
									Decide whether each system is linear or nonlinear.
								</p>
							</statement>
							<choices randomize="yes">
								<choice correct="yes">
									<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = 2x + 3y,\\y' = -x + y\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
								</choice>
								<choice correct="no">
									<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = xy, \\ y' = x - y^2\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
									<feedback><p>The product <m>xy</m> and the square <m>y^2</m> make this nonlinear.</p></feedback>
								</choice>
								<choice correct="yes">
									<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = -4x + y, \\ y' = 5y\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
								</choice>
								<choice correct="no">
									<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = e^x + y, \\ y' = -y\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
									<feedback><p>The <m>e^x</m> term makes this nonlinear.</p></feedback>
								</choice>
							</choices>
						</task>

						<task label="rq-lin-1">
							<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e>  Identify Each System</title>
							<statement>
								<p>Select the linear systems.</p>
							</statement>
							<choices randomize="yes">
								<choice correct="yes">
									<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = 4x - y,\\ y' = 2x + 3y\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
								</choice>
								<choice correct="no">
									<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = xy,\\ y' = x - y^2\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
								</choice>
								<choice correct="yes">
									<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = -y,\\ y' = x\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
								</choice>
								<choice correct="no">
									<statement><m>\ds\quad\left\{\ \begin{array}{l} x' = \sin x + y,\\ y' = x\end{array}\right.</m></statement>
								</choice>
							</choices>
						</task>

						<task label="rq-mat-1">
							<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e>  Benefits</title>
							<statement>
								<p>Choose all advantages of writing <m>\frac{dY}{dt} = AY</m>.</p>
							</statement>
							<choices randomize="yes">
								<choice correct="yes">
									<statement><p>It condenses multiple equations into one.</p></statement>
								</choice>
								<choice correct="yes">
									<statement><p>It links the system to eigenvalues and eigenvectors.</p></statement>
								</choice>
								<choice correct="no">
									<statement><p>It turns any nonlinear system into a linear one.</p></statement>
								</choice>
								<choice correct="no">
									<statement><p>It eliminates the need for initial conditions.</p></statement>
								</choice>
							</choices>
						</task>
				</exercise>
			</paragraphs>
		</p>
	</assemblage>

	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<!-- WRAP-UP + READING QUESTIONS                                      -->
	<!-- ================================================================ -->
	<subsection label="linear-systems-basics-wrap-up">
		<title>üì§ Wrap-Up</title>

		<assemblage label="linear-systems-basics-wrap-up-takeaways">
			<p>
				üóùÔ∏è <m>\textbf{Key Takeaways...}</m>
				<ul marker="square">
					<li></li>
				</ul>
			</p>
		</assemblage>
		<paragraphs label="linear-systems-basics-cyu">
			<title>Check Your Understanding</title>

			<exercise label="linear-systems-basics-cyu-bundle">
				<title><e component="emoji">ü§îüí≠</e> Separation of Variables Reading Questions</title>

				<task label="linear-systems-basics-cyu-1">
					<title><e component="emoji">ü§îüí≠</e> SOV and Nonlinear Equations</title>
					<statement correct="no">
						<p>
							The separation of variables method cannot be applied to non-linear differential equations.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Being able to solve non-linear differential equations is one of the strengths of the separation of variables method.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</task>
				<task label="linear-systems-basics-cyu-2">
					<title><e component="emoji">ü§îüí≠</e> Sort the Steps in Order</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							CONVERT TO PARSONS.. Suppose you want to use separation of variables method to determine the general solution of the differential equation
							<men xml:id="chkpt-linear-systems-basics-examples-1-eqn">
								\ds \frac{dq}{dt} - 3qt^2 = 2q
							</men>.
						</p>
						<p>
							Match the scrambled tasks (on the left) to the task order (on the right) that it should be performed to use this method.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Review the <xref ref="linear-systems-basics" text="custom">SOV Method</xref>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
					<cardsort>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									Equation is 1st-order ‚úÖ
								</p>
							</premise>
							
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 1}</m>
								</p>
							</response>
						</match>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<m>\ds \frac{dq}{dt} = q(2 + 3t^2)</m>
								</p>
							</premise>
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 2}</m>
								</p>
							</response>
						</match>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<m>\ds \frac{1}{q}\ dq = (2 + 3t^2)\ dt</m>
								</p>
							</premise>
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 3}</m>
								</p>
							</response>
						</match>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<m>\ds \int \frac{1}{q} dq = \int (2 + 3t^2) dt</m>
								</p>
							</premise>
							
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 4}</m>
								</p>
							</response>
						</match>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<line><m>\ds \ln|q| = 2t^2 + t^3 + c</m></line>
								</p>
							</premise>
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 5}</m>
								</p>	
							</response>
						</match>
						<match>
							<premise>
								<p>
									<line><m>\ds q = c e\vphantom{|}^{\large 2t^2 + t^3}</m></line>
								</p>
							</premise>
							<response>
								<p>
									<m>\text{Task 6}</m>
								</p>
							</response>
						</match>
					</cardsort>
				</task>
				<task label="linear-systems-basics-cyu-3">
					<title><e component="emoji">ü§îüí≠</e> Combining Constants</title>

					<statement>
						<p>
							Which of the following are valid ways to combine constants when finalizing your solution? Select ALL that apply.
						</p>
					</statement>
					<choices randomize="yes">
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										|y|	\amp = e^{2x + c_1}\\ 
										y	\amp = c_2 e^{2x} 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2=\pm e^{c_1}</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct, since
									<md>
										<mrow>	|y|	\amp =,	e^{2x + c_1}										</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\pm e^{2x + c_1}									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\pm e^{2x} \cdot e^{c_1}							</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	c_2 e^{2x}	\quad \text{where } c_2 = \pm e^{c_1}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										\frac{y^2}{2} \amp = \sin(x) + c_1\\ 
										y^2 \amp = 2\sin(x) + c_2 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2 = 2c_1</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct, since
									<md>
										<mrow>	\frac{y^2}{2}	\amp =,	\sin(x) + c_1									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y^2				\amp =,	\sin(x) + 2c_1									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y^2				\amp =,	2\sin(x) + c_2	\quad \text{where } c_2 = 2c_1	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										y^2	\amp = 2\sin(x) + c_2\\ 
										y	\amp = \pm\sqrt{2\sin(x)} + c_3 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_3=\pm \sqrt{c_2}</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect, you should not combine constants here since <m>\quad\sqrt{A + B} \neq \sqrt{A} + \sqrt{B}</m>.
								</p>

								<p>
									Your solution should be written as
									<md>
										<mrow>	y^2	\amp =,	2\sin(x) + c_2											</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\pm\sqrt{2\sin(x) + c_2}\quad \leftarrow\text{ done}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										e^y	\amp =	3y + c_1\\ 
										y	\amp =	\ln(3y) + c_2 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2= \ln(c_1)</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								
								<p>
									Incorrect, you should not combine constants here since <m>\ln(A + B) \neq \ln(A) + \ln(B)</m>.
								</p>

								<p>
									Your solution should be
									<md>
										<mrow>	e^y	\amp =,	3y + c_1									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\ln(3y + c_1)\quad \leftarrow\text{ done}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice>
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										xy	\amp =	e^x + c_1\\ 
										y	\amp =	\frac{e^x}{x} + c_2 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>\ds c_2=\frac{c_1}{x}</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Incorrect, you should not combine constants here since <m>\frac{c_1}{x}</m> is not constant. Instead your solution should be left as
									<md>
										<mrow>	xy	\amp =,	e^x + c_1													</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\frac{e^x + c_1}{x}											</mrow>
										<mrow>	y	\amp =,	\frac{e^x}{x} + \frac{c_1}{x}\quad \leftarrow\text{ done}	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
						<choice correct="yes">
							<statement>
								<m>
									\quad \left\{
									\begin{align}
										\sqrt{y}	\amp =	c_1e^{3x}\\ 
										y			\amp =	c_2\, e^{6x} 
									\end{align}
									\right.\qquad
								</m> 
								where <m>c_2= c_1^2</m>.
							</statement>
							<feedback>
								<p>
									Correct, since
									<md>
										<mrow>	\sqrt{y}	\amp =,	c_1e^{3x}									</mrow>
										<mrow>	y			\amp =,	(c_1e^{3x})^2								</mrow>
										<mrow>	y			\amp =,	c_1^2(e^{3x})^2								</mrow>
										<mrow>	y			\amp =,	c_2\, e^{6x}\quad \text{where } c_2 = c_1^2	</mrow>
									</md>
								</p>
							</feedback>
						</choice>
					</choices>
				</task>
			</exercise>
		</paragraphs>
	</subsection>
